data.value: Perform one-way ANOVA.
The one-way ANOVA tests the null hypothesis that two or more groups have the same population mean.  The test is applied to samples from two or more groups, possibly with differing sizes.
The sample measurements for each group.  There must be at least two arguments.  If the arrays are multidimensional, then all the dimensions of the array must be the same except for
Axis of the input arrays along which the test is applied. Default is 0.
The computed F statistic of the test.
The associated p-value from the F distribution.

is returned for the F statistic and the p-value in these cases.
The ANOVA test has important assumptions that must be satisfied in order for the associated p-value to be valid.
1. The samples are independent. 2. Each sample is from a normally distributed population. 3. The population standard deviations of the groups are all equal.  This
property is known as homoscedasticity.
If these assumptions are not true for a given set of data, it may still be possible to use the Kruskal-Wallis H-test (
) although with some loss of power.
The length of each group must be at least one, and there must be at least one group with length greater than one.  If these conditions are not satisfied, a warning is generated and (
